import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import gamma, nbinom

# Setting seed for reproducibility
np.random.seed(42)

# Generating bulk RNA-seq dataset
num_genes = 5000
num_samples = 10

# Simulating counts for genes and samples using a gamma distribution
shape_param = 2  # Shape parameter for gamma distribution
scale_param = 100  # Scale parameter for gamma distribution

counts_data = np.random.gamma(shape_param, scale_param, size=(num_genes, num_samples)).astype(int)

# Assigning sample names and gene names
sample_names = [f"Sample_{i}" for i in range(1, num_samples + 1)]
gene_names = [f"Gene_{i}" for i in range(1, num_genes + 1)]

# Creating a DataFrame for counts
counts_df = pd.DataFrame(counts_data, index=gene_names, columns=sample_names)

# Display a portion of the counts DataFrame
print(counts_df.head(10))

pca_df = pd.DataFrame(data=pca_result, columns=['PC1', 'PC2'], index=data.columns)

PCA Visualization

</b> Each point in the plot represents a sample projected onto the two principal components (PC1 and PC2).

By visualizing samples in this reduced-dimensional space, the plot allows for the exploration of patterns, relationships, or separations between samples based on their distribution along the first and second principal components.

The x-axis represents PC1, and the y-axis represents PC2, which capture the highest variance within the data.

This visualization aids in understanding the overall structure or clustering tendencies present in the dataset.

In [29]:

plt.title('PCA Visualization')
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1 (PC1)')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2 (PC2)')
plt.show()

KMeans clustering visualization

</b>

Each point in the plot represents a sample projected onto the two principal components (PC1 and PC2), with colors representing different clusters obtained from a clustering algorithm (that is, K-means).

The plot demonstrates the separation or grouping of samples based on their similarity in high-dimensional space, as represented by their positions in the lower-dimensional PCA space.

The legend displays different clusters, allowing for visual interpretation of sample groupings or clusters in a reduced-dimensional space.

Vocano plot

</b>

A Volcano Plot is a concise visualization displaying log2 fold changes (x-axis) and -log10-transformed p-values (y-axis) for genes in two conditions.

Genes with significant changes and high significance appear further away from the center, with the threshold line indicating significance level.

The plots helps identify highly differentially expressed genes based on their magnitude of change and statistical significance.

In [33]:
# Having calculated differential expression between two conditions and have log2 fold change and p-values,
# We generate random log2 fold change and p-values for demonstration
log2_fold_change = np.random.uniform(low=-2, high=2, size=num_genes)
p_values = np.random.rand(num_genes) * 0.05  # Random p-values

# Volcano plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(log2_fold_change, -np.log10(p_values), color='blue', alpha=0.5)
plt.axhline(-np.log10(0.05), color='red', linestyle='--', label='Threshold')
plt.axvline(0, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=0.5)
plt.title('Volcano Plot')
plt.xlabel('Log2 Fold Change')
plt.ylabel('-log10(p-value)')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Gene expression distribution

</b>

This histogram visualizes the distribution of gene expression levels for a single sample (Sample_1).

It shows the frequency or count of genes at different expression levels within Sample_1. The bins represent ranges of expression values, and the KDE (Kernel Density Estimate) curve depicts the estimated probability density of the expression values
